From Clingmans Dome Parking Area follow paved trail towards the lookout tower.  Past the visitor center about 0.2 mile  there is a concrete bench on the right side of the trail.  This bench is the first reference point to a Red Spruce with a diameter of 21.2 cm.  It is about 50 meters at 20 degrees from the bench..  The next tree is a Red Spruce with a diameter of 50.2 cm at 25 degrees.  This Spruce is on the ridge.  The next Spruce is about 30 meters at 38 degrees with a diameter of 23 cm. From this tree the top right corner of the hectare ATBI Plot is 55 degrees at about 25 meters.  This corner is marked with a thin red electric fence post about 3 feet tall.  All tree tags are marked "ATBI".  The hectare is marked off with nylon string around the parameter.  The Long Term Monitoring Plot is also marked with string.  Do not disturb the Long Term Monitoring Plot.

The Customer Receivables Aging dashboard provides an analysis of a company's accounts receivables and key accounts status. It shows the percentage distribution of overdue receivables and future remit, an historical trend of aging amounts, forecasted remit amounts, and the breakdown of these amounts for the top five customers or sales employees.

Application settings determine how colors are sent to the printer
Color rendering styles selection does not change how colors appear on output

Some applications describe the colors you pick in terms of how much red, green, and blue (RGB) should be used to make the color.  Other applications describe the colors in terms of how much cyan, magenta, yellow, and black (CMYK) should be used to make the color.  The IBM Network Color Printer uses the CMYK toner system to make colors.   When an application describes colors to the printer as RGB, the printer controller must translate that color into CMYK.  The Rendering Style option is offered to give you a choice of how to balance the colors for the kind of output you need when the RGB to CMYK takes place.

1.  Follow the steps below to verify that the printer works. a.  Unplug the parallel cable from the back of the HP LaserJet series printer, so the printer is not receiving any information from the computer.  Unplug the network cable (if equipped) so the printer is not receiving any information from the network. b.  Ensure that the HP LaserJet series printer is turned on and is in the ready state (no errors). c.  Print a self-test from the HP LaserJet series printer.  The method for printing a self-test is different depending on the printer model.  check the User's Guide that came with the HP product for instructions.  - If the self-test prints a blank page,, check to make sure that the tape has been removed from the print cartridge.  - If nothing prints, try plugging the HP LaserJet series printer directly into another wall outlet.  The power cable may be faulty.  Try another power cable to plug in the printer into the wall outlet.  If the printer still will not print, it may need to be serviced.
